How much data are sufficient for A/B testing?

Maiia Bakhova
May 27, 2018

For what A/B testing is used

  • Email subject lines: Test different subject lines against to increase your open rates.
  • Calls-to-action: Which version boosts conversions[1]?
  • Layouts, colors and fonts: Changing the colors and fonts can help or hurt.
  • Navigation: Test different types of navigation to determine how users prefer to interact with your website.
  • Images: Choosing logo or ad photo can be optimized instead of guessing.
  • Content length: It changes with audience, product and other factors.
  • Direct mailings: Which mailings drive more leads to a website landing page or phone calls to your business.
  • Billboards: These old-school methods still work, and we can test their influence.
  • TV commercials: Track which version drives more leads for your business.
  • Business cards: Handing out business cards is a simple yet effective way to build your brand.
  • Radio spots: Airing radio spots is a great way to build local awareness of your brand.

A Data Size Restriction Problems

A general advice is to get at least 1000 page visitors and to gather data at least for a week. But we do not know would it be enough or not.

  • Business demands
  • Gathering data can be costly.
  • Conditions may change quicker than data is collecting.
  • Imbalanced data
  • Technical implementations
  • Legal requirements

A Data Collection Methods

  • Google Analytics
  • Adobe Website Analytics
  • Sales Department
  • Third Party Data

A considered example

A/B testing started as comparison of 2 features, but now it includes multivariate cases as well.

For this particular presentation I will consider a few ads which are supposed to be displayed on a web page. We want to determine an ad which gets the most clicks.

The car pictures are provided as an illustration. My data will be randomly generated and not taken from real life. They are represented as a table where we have a column for each ad and is it randomly populated with 0s and 1s. Percentage of 1s represents conversion rate.

Problem implementation

I assume that we have a paid spot on a website where we are to display one image. We have 10 images and we control how we display them. We have the following options for our data analysis: we can compute means and estimate their possible errors. The last one is crucial for decisions on our data credibility.

A confidence interval

A confidence interval (CI) is a type of interval estimate (of a population parameter) that is computed from the observed data. The confidence level is the frequency (i.e., the proportion) of possible confidence intervals that contain the true value of their corresponding parameter. In other words, if confidence intervals are constructed using a given confidence level in an infinite number of independent experiments, the proportion of those intervals that contain the true value of the parameter will match the confidence level.

There are traditional statistical and empirical ways of CI calculation.

A Traditional Statistical Approach

An Empirical Approach: bootstrapping mean rates.

A Multi-bandit approach

The idea behind the Multi-bandit approach is to adjust our displays during data collection to learn what is more important for us. Let us assume that in this particular case we want to know what rate is the greatest and we would like to reduce amount of time and money on ads which do not perform well.
